shared_text:
Thermalito Union Elementary School District
September 9 at 9:00 PM ¬∑

Dear Thermalito Families:

The challenges just keep on coming - with the area fires, we have friends, family and neighbors evacuated from their homes. The ash fall in our area is substantial and the air quality is poor. Because of the current environmental conditions and the unpredictable nature of this fire we are not going to add any new lessons for students on Thursday and Friday. We are also not requiring students to log into classroom sessions until Monday. Today, Thursday and Friday will not be considered unexcused absences for attendance purposes. We also have to cancel meal distributions for the remainder of this week. Please stay tuned to our social media and website for updates for when it will resume (we hope early next week). Take care of yourselves as you navigate the uncertainty of the next few days. Good bye for now.

post_text: The Temporary Evacuation Point has been relocated to the Gridley Fairgrounds located at 199 E. Hazel Street in Gridley. Residents are asked to please remain in your vehicle. Representatives from Butte County and American Red Cross will assist you with further information and sheltering needs. When evacuating, take your animals with you. Make sure to bring water, food, bedding, and any containment devices necessary. If you have larger animals or livestock that you are unable to take with you, they should be left in open pastures. Do not leave animals locked in a barn or other large structure. Animal shelters are currently at capacity. For the most updated information, please visit https://www.buttecounty.net/ or call the Animal Sheltering Hotline: 530-895-0000

post_text:
Due to mandatory evacuations and evacuation warnings in the Oroville area, please note: All BCOE offices, school sites, and programs in the Oroville area are closed today, September 9, 2020. Emergency information is available on the Butte County Sheriff‚Äôs website. https://www.buttecounty.net/sheriffcoroner/

Please take care of your family and yourselves. Remember that your social-emotional wellbeing is a vital part of your overall wellness. When you are in a safe place, if you or someone you know needs to talk with someone, anyone can call the Disaster Distress Hotline at 1-800-985-5990 or text TalkWithUs to 66746 to speak to a caring counselor. You can call Butte County Behavioral Health at 800-334-6622 or 530-891-2810. You can also visit the Butte County Behavioral Health website for additional resources. https://www.buttecounty.net/behavioralhealth/

We are strong, we are resilient, and we are prepared to handle this situation. Together, we will get through this because we are Butte Strong. Stay safe, everyone.

September is #suicidepreventionmonth and next week kicks off #suicidepreventionweek2020 Individuals and organizations around the world join their voices to broadcast the message that suicide is preventable. We know that our community is facing unprecedented times, and we want to share resources and tips that can help you or a loved one during this time. Remember, your life matters.
Check out the Behavioral Health Service Guide for Butte County: http://www.namibutteco.com/wp-content/uploads/BCDBH-Service-Guide.pdf
Take your Brain Health Temperature and recognize signs of stress and anxiety: https://growingupchico.com/take-your-brain-health-temperature-to-stay-mentally-healthy/ #bcoecares #ButteSchoolsStrong #bcoeschools #themindmatters #socialemotionalwellness

Growing Up Chico Magazine
June 9 at 1:35 AM ¬∑

The Chico Unified Nutrition Services Department is offering FREE curbside meals all summer!

Meals are served on Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays. During this time, two lunches and two breakfast meals will be provided for each child! Children can receive six days of meals with only three days of leaving the house!

Meals are available on Monday, Wednesday and Friday from 11 a.m. - 12:30 p.m.

Serving locations are:

¬∑ Bidwell Junior High

¬∑ Chico Junior High

¬∑ Citrus Elementary

¬∑ Chapman Elementary

¬∑ Little Chico Creek Elementary

* Please note: Children must be present to receive a meal. Free meals are available to any child in the community age 18 years or younger (regardless of school).

* Schedule note: The Summer Feeding Program runs from 6/8/20-8/14/20. There will be no food service on Friday, July 3, 2020.

Any changes or schedule updates will be posted on the website.

üéì We are so excited to announce that Inspire will be hosting a drive-in movie event at the Silver Dollar Fairgrounds to celebrate our senior class of 2020, today, Wednesday, June 3 from 6:30 ‚Äì 8:30.

We know that parents and students have been hoping for some kind of community event, and we hope that this celebration helps to meet that need.

For those of you that want to participate in person, please remember it will be vital for everyone to follow the guidelines for a safe and positive evening of fun and celebration.

The drive-in is OPTIONAL, and an at-home watch party is encouraged. Parents and community members can access the virtual graduation video at any point after 6:30 p.m. on June, 3rd. We highly suggest cozying up with a bag of popcorn, a popsicle (or two), and a huge box of tissues!

You can view the video by visiting

www.inspirechico.org/events

or directly at YouTube by visiting

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tc2ztJ7pwq0&feature=youtu.be

We are so grateful to our custodial team! They have been working hard to sanitize and beautify our school campuses.

Did you know?
‚Ä¢ Landscaping and grounds staff have planted over 250 new foliage, plants and trees.
‚Ä¢ Maintenance & Operations staff have completed 117 work orders over the last 65 days.
‚Ä¢ Wall-mounted hand sanitizer dispensers have been installed in every office and all nurse offices. Staff continues to install wall-mounted hand sanitizer dispensers in each classroom. Once complete, 700 new dispensers will be installed!

As we celebrate Classified Appreciation Week, we have to say thank you for making our campuses so clean and beautiful!

Chico Country Day School
May 15 at 1:30 PM ¬∑

May is Mental Health Matters Month. Every Friday this month, we will highlight different ways we can focus on our mental health.

This week's tip is all about kindness. Studies show that simple acts of kindness can boost our immune systems by reducing stress and heighten the production of the ‚Äúfeel good‚Äù hormones in our brains. During this period of physical distancing, many of us may be experiencing loneliness at much higher levels than ever before. The simple act of kindness is something that can help us stay connected while also reducing the negative effects of loneliness. Just another reason why its cool to be kind!

Follow the #eachmindmatters campaign for more ways we can focus on our mental health.

#MentalHealthMattersMonth
#weareccds

shared_text:
California Department of Education
May 6 at 8:35 PM ¬∑

California School for the Deaf - Fremont's CORE department (Curriculum, Outreach, Resources, and Education) is proud to present the CORE Learning Channel. An online learning tool created entirely for California deaf students of all ages, their families, and teachers, it provides accessible resources and information while our students are learning at home: COVID-19 information, academic sites in ASL, visually-accessible sites worth investigating, games, workouts, storytelling, and resources across the curriculum.

Visit it here: https://sites.google.com/csdeagles.net/core-learning-channel/home

post_text: Thank you Chico Rotary for your continued support of our #ButteCounty schools! #ButteCOE #ButteSchoolsStrong
shared_text:
Chico High School
April 30 at 1:05 PM ¬∑

Senior Families - Although we missed Wood Works Wonder (aka Birdhouse Build), The Rotary Club of Chico and Chico Building have stepped up to make this event come alive. They will provide kits for seniors to make a birdhouse from home, at no cost. Once done, we hope to display and honor our Seniors of the Class of 2020. The Rotary Club will pre-cut the wood and pre-drill for the screws. We will provide the screws. Register via the link in our bio for your free kit and let us know what other supplies you need. We also can supply things such as paint, brushes, wood glue, tile, roofing shingles and a screwdriver. We have a limited supply of these items.
If you can donate any supplies to help we would be so appreciative. Email us at: info@chicohighsobergradnight.com
Please register for a birdhouse kit by May 5th! We will have them available for pick up or delivery between May 11th-13th. The birdhouses need to be completed by May 25th. We will let you know how we will proceed with displaying them based on our community guidelines.
‚ù§Ô∏èSober Grad Night Committee

We want to share our love, recognize their achievements and celebrate them with ‚ÄúClass of 2020 Yard Signs.‚Äù Let‚Äôs put them in yards all over Chico ‚Äì buy them for your house, grandparents houses, family and friends.

We are selling the signs at below cost ($5) and will have 2 porch delivery pick up sites in Chico when they are available. If you purchase 5 or more, we will deliver them for free! ‚ù§Ô∏èüéìüíõ
www.chicohighsobergradnight.com
üòªWhile we can‚Äôt predict what the end of the year is going to look like, we are working hard to make alternative plans. So, keep on making those memory boards (see more information on our website). We will come up with a plan to showcase them in some way!
.
.
#classof2020 #chico #chicohigh #chicohigh #panthernation #itsagreatdaytobeapanther

post_text: Don't miss this virtual play presented by Inspire School of Arts and Sciences! #ButteCOE #ButteSchoolsStrong
shared_text:
Inspire School of Arts and Sciences
April 22 at 7:35 PM ¬∑

We are so excited to announce that we will be presenting our very first digital play, "10 Ways To Survive Life in a Quarantine," May 8th and 9th!

Set a reminder to:
- order in your favorite local food
- cozy up with the fam
- and subscribe to our Patreon account to view some incredible digital performing arts content!

All of the subscriptions support the performing arts clubs at Inspire. Monthly subscriptions start at $1! You can't beat that.

Remember, you have to subscribe to see the play and it will ONLY be available May 8th and 9th. Here's the link: https://www.patreon.com/inspiretheatre

#InspireUsAtHome #InspireChico

post_text:
Hey Facebook friends. Our Human Resources Department is updating the Employment Opportunities and the link is below. Even though our offices are closed, our HR Specialists are working remotely throughout the day updating the recruitment announcements and posting them to the Employment Opportunities! Share with a friend, family member or someone you know who may be looking for a job. Also share out that once our offices open back up, we would love for folks to sign up for our variety of substitute lists.

These are unprecedented times but our HR Team is here to answer questions and/or emails. If you call one of their phone lines at the office they are checking voicemails from their home offices throughout the day, so leave a message and someone will get back to you.

Stay safe and well!

Later, join California Natural Resources Agency Secretary Crowfoot w/ special guest speakers as they talk today‚Äôs current climate in the afternoon. April 8 at 5:19 PM ¬∑

A #BetterButte begins with you! We know times are challenging right now. Being home all day isn‚Äôt easy and it can be especially hard with young children. People across the nation are doing creative things to stay busy and healthy at home. All of the precautions in place for COVID-19, including the stay at home order, are to protect you, your family and the community. We might be partial, but we‚Äôre pretty sure we have some of the most creative residents right here in Butte County! Show us what you‚Äôre doing to be a #BetterButte. post_text: #ButteCounty, Let's join our Public Health Department and post words of encouragement, messages of gratitude or healthy choices during this difficult time. Use the #BetterButte! #ButteCOE
shared_text:
Butte County Public Health
April 3 at 4:22 PM ¬∑

Reports from the Bay Area indicate the stay at home order is working. We can do this Butte County! Thank you for your continued diligence and commitment to each other. Stay home. If you need to go out for essential activities, maintain your space (at least 6 feet from others) and you may choose to cover your face with a cloth face covering. You can use a mask if you already have one, if not, save those for our healthcare workers.
#BetterButte
